The U.S. and Germany issued a joint statement in July 2021 outlining commitments to support Ukraine’s energy security, impose sanctions if Russia uses energy as a weapon, and pursue shared climate goals. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4"] Germany pledged to “take action at the national level and press for effective measures at the European level, including sanctions,” should Russia threaten Ukraine’s energy supplies. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_1.3"] Both countries agreed that continued transit of Russian gas via Ukraine beyond 2024 was in Europe’s interest, and Germany committed to appointing a special envoy to facilitate an extension of up to 10 years. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4","msmarco_v2.1_doc_3.2"] Germany further committed to safeguarding and increasing reverse-flow capacity to Ukraine—measures described by analysts as “decent though non-binding.” ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.4","msmarco_v2.1_doc_4.1"] The agreement established a Climate and Energy Partnership featuring a “Green Fund for Ukraine,” with an initial German contribution of at least $175 million and a goal to mobilize $1 billion for decarbonization projects. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_5.3","msmarco_v2.1_doc_6.1"] Ukraine and Poland immediately criticized the deal as insufficiently binding to protect Ukraine’s security interests. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_3.2"] Maria Shagina’s article accurately summarizes these commitments but foregrounds critiques about their enforceability and lack of concrete implementation mechanisms, reflecting a common analytical view of the agreement’s limitations. ["msmarco_v2.1_doc_4.1"]